To be more serious, I know that antivirus software companies have been selling products for 20+ years that, supposedly, execute suspect stuff in a sandbox to see what it does as part of inspection. It used to be called "heuristic analysis" or some variant on that. Only the people writing malware like to have it check system properties and look for a "MicroSoft" brand motherboard, which is usually how the virtual machine in the sandbox identifies itself. So the malware is written not to misbehave when it knows it's being watched. And polymorphic engines that compile with random back-and-forth jumps that remove the patterns most antivirus software looks for have been around since the dialup days and are only getting more common. As well as the polymorphic viruses that rewrite themselves and rearrange their own bits to evade recognition.

There are some very bright minds out there writing this stuff. People have this misconception from 1980s movies that "hackers" are misunderstood teenagers playing a prank. No, it's a trillion dollar business now and these people have organized crime and nation state actors providing resources to develop this stuff. *cough* NSA *cough*
